{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0185Bi67gBC9PHqm37XjnKfN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I don't have an `openssl-toolbox` pod running - only `curl-test`. I need to:\n\n1. Deploy the openssl-toolbox pod to generate certs, OR use my local `openssl` to generate the certs\n2. Create the secrets\n3. Tear down the existing ES 7.17.9 cluster\n4. Deploy ES 8.11.1 with proper TLS configuration\n\nLet me use local openssl since it's simpler. I'll generate the certs locally and create the secrets directly.\n\nHere's my plan:\n\n**Step 1: Generate TLS certificates**\n- Create CA cert\n- Create server cert with proper SANs (including `es-http` hostname as the service name)\n\n**Step 2: Create secrets**\n- `es-http-tls`: with tls.crt, tls.key, ca.crt\n- `elastic-password`: with password key\n\n**Step 3: Update ConfigMap** \n- Add ES 8.11.1 specific settings (xpack.security, initial_master_nodes)\n\n**Step 4: Delete old StatefulSet**\n\n**Step 5: Create new StatefulSet with ES 8.11.1**\n- Mount TLS secrets\n- Set ELASTIC_PASSWORD env var\n- Configure security via environment variables\n\nI need to generate the certificates first, covering all the necessary SANs for the Elasticsearch service including the Kubernetes DNS names and wildcard for inter-node communication, plus localhost and 127.0.0.1. For transport layer TLS between nodes, I'll use certificate verification mode to skip hostname validation. The key thing to remember is that ES 8.x separates HTTP TLS (port 9200) from transport TLS (port 9300), and the HTTP cert needs to match the `es-http` service name that the curl test will be connecting to.\n\nWriting the certificate generation script... Writing shell commands... Writing config YAML...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":957,"cache_read_input_tokens":57822,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_