{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NcvEDt3HeU9Tdd4KD2Z4HV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. The existing StatefulSet uses PVCs (`volumeClaimTemplates` with `data`, 5Gi storage). So each pod has a PVC.\n\nFor the new ES 8.11.1 deployment, I need to:\n1. Delete the old StatefulSet (but NOT the PVCs, which we don't need for a fresh deployment anyway — actually if we keep the PVCs from ES 7.17.9, they'll be used by the new pods and might cause issues. Better to delete them too)\n2. Deploy the new StatefulSet with ES 8.11.1, also using PVCs for consistency with the existing setup. But I need to be careful here — if I delete the StatefulSet while keeping the PVCs, the new StatefulSet will reuse those existing volumes, which still contain the old ES 7.17.9 data and could cause compatibility issues.\n\nThe cleanest approach for a test environment is to delete both the StatefulSet and the existing PVCs, then create fresh ones with the new StatefulSet so ES 8.11.1 starts with a clean slate.\n\nFor ES 8.x security, I need to account for a few key requirements: security is enabled by default, transport TLS is mandatory when security is on, and I must set `cluster.initial_master_nodes` so the cluster can form. The `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable will set the built-in elastic user password during first startup. Now I'll write out the YAML manifests, starting with generating TLS certificates using openssl locally.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2114,"cache_read_input_tokens":58779,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2114},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8d3fdde4-c7f2-4476-8190-13d1882a5e4c","uuid":"667a0308-aca5-405e-